ee96aad6-7641-4802-a831-376039f16395.5de7dd51-393b-4986-99f2-7d5f6c6ecc36.description=
This operation executes a command from the command line of a remote RAS. 
When running on Unix, you cannot determine the type of shell to be used (sh, bash, ksh, csh, etc), so make sure to include the shell in your command if you want to perform operations such as file redirection.  
Example\: sh -c "ls -lha /etc > /tmp/myfile".

When running on Windows, this command  prepends "cmd.exe /C" or "command.exe /C" to the command you specify, so there is no need to pass this information to the operation.

Inputs\:
    command - The command to execute.
    arguments - Any arguments needed for the command.
    environment - Specifies environment variables/values that need to be defined when running the command.
    path - The path to the commands executable.
    cmd_timeout - Timeout in milliseconds before the command is considered as having failed when "returnImmediately" is false.
Default value\: 100000 (100 seconds).
    returnImmediately - If "true", the operation executes the command and returns a result immediately.  It does not wait for the command to finish.
Valid values\: true, false.
Default value\: false.

Results\:
    STDOUT - The standard output of the command.
    STDERR - The standard error output of the command.
    exitStatus - Every command returns an exit status (sometimes referred to as a return status or exit code). A successful command returns 0, while an unsuccessful one returns a non-zero value that usually can be interpreted as an error code.

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.


Example\:
   This is a valid input example for executing a "ping" command from a Windows machine\:
    command\: ping
    arguments\: example.server.com
ee96aad6-7641-4802-a831-376039f16395.60ac7e7b-c407-49f5-8cfc-d95339897cd8.description=
 Apply a guest customization spec to an existing VM.

Inputs\:
    host - VMWare vCenter hostname or IP.
    user - VMWare username.
    password - VMWare user's password.
    port - Port to connect on.
    protocol - Connection protocol.
Valid values\: "https", "http"
    closeSession - Close the internally kept VMWare Infrastructure API session at completion of operation.
Valid values\: "true", "false"
    async - Asynchronously perform the task.
Valid values\: "true", "false"
    taskTimeOut - Time to wait before the operation is considered to have failed (seconds).
    vmIdentifierType - Virtual machine identifier type (inventorypath, name, ip, hostname, uuid, vmid).
    virtualMachine - Primary Virtual Machine identifier. Inventorypath (Datacenter/vm/Folder/MyVM), Name of VM, IP (IPv4 or IPv6 depending upon ESX version), hostname (full), UUID, or the VM id (vm-123,123).
    vmDatacenter - Virtual machine's datacenter.
    customizationTemplateName - Name of the customization specification to apply to the virtual machine. The customization specification should already exist in the vCenter customization specifications manager. This is not a required input. However, if  both 'customizationTemplateName' and 'customizationSpecXml' are empty or have input, the operation will give an error message and fail. Hence, either 'customizationTemplateName' or 'customizationSpecXml' should have an input.
    customizationSpecXml - The Xml string of the customization spec to apply. This is not a required input.

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed successfully.
    failure - Something went wrong.

Returns\:
    returnResult - Operation result message.

Notes\:
1>Inventory Path Formatting\: If host is an ESX server inventory path will be\: ha-datacenter/vm/ .  If host is a vCenter the inventory path will be\: /vm// . The / part of the path is based on the "Virtual Machines & Templates" view in the vCenter client. The inventory path is case sensitive.

2>Guest customization spec can be applied only to a vm.

3>If the operation fails due to "A customization operation is pending on the vm\: ", then restart the guest of the vm before applying a different customization specification.

4>The result of the VMware/VMware Virtual Infrastructure and vSphere/Guest/Export Guest Customization Spec operation can be used to get the customizationSpecXml input value.

5>If the Microsoft Sysprep Tools for a particular windows guest operating system is not already bundled with the vCenter Server then it must be installed on the vCenter Server system. For instructions on Guest Operating System Customization Requirements see "Customizing Guest Operating Systems" on page-42 in http\://www.vmware.com/pdf/vsphere4/r41/vsp_41_vm_admin_guide.pdf
ee96aad6-7641-4802-a831-376039f16395.639f4ec1-f3cd-4194-86fc-9253f220e1ac.description=
Useful Op to keep a running results.
Takes a string input (resultText) and appends this to a global context key of "runningResults". As a result, the context key whose name is in the keyName input will be appended with the string from the input resultText.

Input Parameters\:
keyName - name of context key to append to
resultText - string input to append
delimiter - (leave blank for none) the delimiter to put between what is already in keyName before appending resultText

Responses\:
success - assigned the context variable

Returns\:
The the value of the context variable it appended to.

Context\:
runningResults

Scriptlet Example\:
currentResults \= scriptletContext.get("runningResults");

if (currentResults \=\= null) {
   currentResults \= resultText;
} else {
   currentResults +\= resultText;
}


scriptletContext.putGlobal("runningResults", currentResults);

ee96aad6-7641-4802-a831-376039f16395.6b23bcce-1943-4b12-a95e-6b0e3c4040aa.description=
This operation checks whether a string matches another string, using a specific matching rule. The "toMatch" input is the string that is checked for matching the "matchTo" expression. 

Inputs\:
    matchType - The type of match to perform.
Valid values\: Exact Match, Contains, Contains Once, Does Not Contain, Match All Words, Match No Words, Regex (The values are not case sensitive)
Default value\: Exact Match
    toMatch - The string that is checked for matching.
    matchTo - The string to match against.
Example\: If "matchType" is “RegEx”, the "matchTo" input is a regular expression such as\: ^-?\d+(([\.,]\d+)?)+$. 
    ignoreCase - Specifies whether to ignore case when matching or not.
Valid values\: False, True
Default value\: False

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. It contains the string "Matches" if the "toMatch" string matches the "matchTo" string. Otherwise, it contains the string "Does Not Match".  

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.

ee96aad6-7641-4802-a831-376039f16395.d5299e30-0467-4812-b3c2-921e67e22a07.description=
Add a Network Interface Card to a virtual machine assigned to a port group / network name.

Inputs\:
host - VMWare host hostname or IP.
user - VMWare username.
password - VMWare user's password.
port - Port to connect on.
protocol - Connection protocol (http or https).
closeSession - Close the internally kept VMWare Infrastructure API session at completion of operation (true, false).
async - Asynchronously perform the task (true, false).
taskTimeOut - Time to wait before the operation is considered to have failed (seconds)
virtualMachine - Primary Virtual Machine identifier. Inventorypath (Datacenter/vm/Folder/MyVM), Name of VM, IP (IPv4 or IPv6 depending upon ESX version), hostname (full), UUID, or the VM id (vm-123,123).
vmIdentifierType - Virtual machine identifier type (inventorypath, name, ip, hostname, uuid, vmid).
vmDatacenter - Virtual machine's datacenter.
netPortGroup - Name of port group to connect this new NIC to. This port group can be a legacy port group or a distributed virtual port group.
netNicType - Virtual network interface card type. Valid inputs\: PCNet32, E1000, VmxNet, VmxNet2, VmxNet3. NIC type VmxNet2 is only supported for virtual machine hardware version 4 and later.  NIC type VmxNet3 is only supported for vitual machine hardware version 7 and later.
netMacAddr - MAC address to assign if netMacGeneration is set to Manual.
netMacGeneration - MAC address assignment. Valid inputs\: Manual, Generated, Assigned (Assigned value is only valid when host is a vCenter server. Will assign MAC from vCenter).
netWakeOnLan - Enable Wake On LAN for the NIC (true, false).

Responses\:
success - The operation completed successfully.
failure - Something went wrong.

Returns\:
returnResult - Task result or operation result.

Notes\:
Inventory Path Formatting\: If host is an ESX server inventory path will be\: ha-datacenter/vm/ .  If host is a vCenter the inventory path will be\: /vm// . The / part of the path is based on the "Virtual Machines & Templates" view in the vCenter client. The inventory path is case sensitive.

ee96aad6-7641-4802-a831-376039f16395.f8b05e3f-19f4-4326-8cf5-0a143e8f0e68.description=
Modifies an existing Network Interface Card (NIC) on a virtual machine. Optional inputs with a "net" and "connect" prefix that are left empty will not be modified on the NIC.

Inputs\:
    host - VMware vCenter, ESX or ESXi host hostname or IP.
    user - VMware username.
    password - VMware user's password.
    port - Port to connect on.
Examples\: 443, 80
    protocol - Connection protocol.
Valid values\: "https", "http"
    closeSession - Close the internally kept VMware Infrastructure API session at completion of operation.
Valid values\: "true", "false"
    async - Asynchronously perform the task.
Valid values\: "true", "false"
    taskTimeOut - Time to wait in seconds before the operation is considered to have failed.
Default value\: 800
    virtualMachine - Primary Virtual Machine identifier. Inventorypath (Datacenter/vm/Folder/MyVM), Name of VM, IP (IPv4 or IPv6 depending upon ESX version), hostname (full), UUID, or the VM id (vm-123,123).
    vmIdentifierType - Virtual machine identifier type 
Valid values\: "inventorypath", "name", "ip", "hostname", "uuid", "vmid"
    vmDatacenter - Virtual machine's datacenter.
    deviceNumber - The NIC number to modify on the VM.  As an example\: "Network Adapter 1" would have be deviceNumber "1".
Examples\: If a VM as a network adapter named "Network Adapter 1" the deviceNumber would be "1".
    netPortGroup - Name of port group to connect this NIC to.  This port group can be a legacy port group or a distributed virtual port group.
Examples\: "VM Network", "dvPortGroup"
    netNicType - Virtual network interface card type. NIC type VmxNet2 is only supported for virtual machine hardware version 4 and later.  NIC type VmxNet3 is only supported for vitual machine hardware version 7 and later.
Valid values\: "PCNet32", "E1000", "VmxNet", "VmxNet2", "VmxNet3"
    netMacAddr - MAC address to assign if netMacGeneration is set to Manual.
Value format\: Six groups of two hexadecimal digits (0-F), separated by colons (\:).
Examples\: 00\:50\:56\:94\:AB\:EF
    netMacGeneration - MAC address assignment method. 
Valid inputs\: "Manual", "Generated", "Assigned" (Assigned value is only valid when host is a vCenter server. Will assign MAC from vCenter).
    netWakeOnLan - Enable Wake On LAN for the NIC.
Valid values\: "true", "false"
    connect - Connect the NIC to the network?  Only applicable when VM is powered on.
Valid values\: "true", "false"
    connectAtPowerOn - Connect the NIC to the network at power on time of VM?
Valid values\: "true", "false"

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed successfully.
    failure - Something went wrong. See returnResult for details.

Returns\:
    returnResult - Task result or operation result

Notes\:
1. Inventory Path Formatting\: If host is an ESX server inventory path will be\: ha-datacenter/vm/ .  If host is a vCenter the inventory path will be\: /vm// . The / part of the path is based on the "Virtual Machines & Templates" view in the vCenter client. The inventory path is case sensitive.
